<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAMS-RAIDERS GAME IS HARD-FOUGHT ON FIELD AND IN STANDS; SPORTS: FOURTEEN FANS 
ARE ARRESTED AND 55 ARE EJECTED AS CAPACITY CROWD LIVES UP TO TRADITIONAL 
UNRULINESS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN ELLINGWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rams and Raiders fans on Sunday celebrated what could be their last game as 
cross-town rivals in their customary way. 
</P>
<P>
 They drank and fought. 
</P>
<P>
 Police counted at least 26 altercations and arrested 14 people -- mostly for 
drunkenness and fighting -- during a sold-out football game that drew 65,208 
spectators and was watched as closely for the battling in the stands as on the 
field. Besides those arrested, 55 fans were ejected for general misbehavior. 
</P>
<P>
 "I saw men just beating on each other rapid fire. I've been to several hockey 
games in St. Louis but never seen crowd fights like at the game today," said 
Rob Harvath, a visiting retail analyst for Anheuser-Busch who watched the game 
-- and the fights -- from the beer company's luxury box. 
</P>
<P>
 The violence, in which no one was seriously injured, might have been worse but 
for the scores of extra police and Anaheim Stadium security personnel placed on 
duty after the last brawl-marred meeting between the teams, a preseason game in 
August during which more than 20 were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
 This time, at least, the fighting waited until the start of the game, which 
the Raiders won 20-17. In August, police reported people were going at it 
during the national anthem. 
</P>
<P>
 "The third quarter started turning kind of south," said Sgt. Gerald Stec, who 
heads the Anaheim police stadium detail. By the fourth quarter, officials had 
turned off the beer spigots to an upper-deck section where as many as two dozen 
people were involved in the afternoon's biggest brawl. 
</P>
<P>
 A clash erupted near the end zone among fans who seemed oblivious to the fact 
that it was a crucial point late in the game and the Rams were about to score 
right in front of them. 
</P>
<P>
 Stec said the added police presence -- groups of a dozen or more uniformed 
officers were posted near end-zone trouble spots -- helped prevent other large 
fights and kept the mayhem to a minimum. He said police were able to stamp out 
most of the skirmishes quickly and without serious injury to fans. 
</P>
<P>
 First-aid workers reported four to five fight-related injuries, but only one 
of those people was taken to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm a season ticket-holder and I'm disgusted by it," said Rams fan Ed Stevens 
of Costa Mesa, who left the game early with his 11-year-old son after watching 
brawls break out in the stands. "It's notorious -- every time the Rams and 
Raiders get together." 
</P>
<P>
 Stevens blamed drinking for the trouble. "I don't think they should serve beer 
when these two teams get together," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Even the cap vendors were steering clear. 
</P>
<P>
 Concessionaire Mike Winn tended a stand high up in the stadium's top level -- 
far away, he hoped, from the kind of scrapping he saw during the August game. 
"There must have been 30 fights," Winn recalled. "I said, put me someplace 
where I can't get hurt." 
</P>
<P>
 The brawling Sunday may have marred history in the making. In view of 
speculation that the Rams may move after this season to St. Louis or Baltimore 
and rumors that the Raiders too may end up elsewhere, it is possible that 
Sunday's game was the last between the Rams and Raiders as local teams. 
</P>
<P>
 "Everybody's talking about that. Keep your tickets -- they might be 
collectibles someday," said longtime Rams season ticket-holder Raymond Steed, a 
Downey iron worker. 
</P>
<P>
 Dan Garcia, whose face was painted in Rams blue and gold, flew from 
Albuquerque, N.M., for the game. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Rams may be leaving soon. This is (for) bragging rights for L.A. before 
the Rams leave," said Garcia, who said he was involved in a pregame scuffle in 
the parking lot after a Raiders fan tried to snare his friend's Rams banner. 
"It got a little bit rowdy," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Steed played down the rivalry between the teams. 
</P>
<P>
 "What it all boils down to is, this is just a game," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's just L.A. It's just the L.A. get-together," said Steed. "There's enough 
violence here. We don't need any more." 
</P>
</TEXT>
