<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; CITY ASSERTS DESIRE TO KEEP WETLANDS A 
BIO-DIVERSITY PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council last week voted to send the county a loud and clear message 
that the city's preference is to keep Bolsa Chica wetlands a bio-diversity 
park. 
</P>
<P>
 The council voted 5 to 2 to ask the county Board of Supervisors to preserve 
the entire wetlands and adjacent land. Supervisors are expected to consider a 
development proposal for Bolsa Chica in December. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilmen Jim Silva and Earle Robitaille cast the opposing votes. The new 
council, with three new members, will take office Dec. 5. The new lineup on the 
council is considered more pro-development than the existing council, but it is 
unclear whether it will take a position on the development. 
</P>
<P>
 The current council also authorized a letter asking the county to include the 
city in negotiations for a development agreement with Koll Real Estate Group. 
Koll is proposing to build 4,286 homes on the property and restore 1,100 acres 
of wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
 The county, however, has proposed alternate plans that include allowing up to 
3,300 homes and construction of a tidal inlet. 
</P>
<P>
 As a bio-diversity park, the entire property would be used for conservation 
purposes with passive recreation uses, native habitat restoration and 
environmental education opportunities. This plan could be realized if the 
property owner agreed to a land swap or purchase of the property. 
</P>
<P>
 But the city, in its comments to the county, also recommended a list of 
guidelines should housing development occur on the wetlands.  
</P>
<P>
 Among the city's suggestions is that a Bolsa Chica project should be a 
financial benefit to the city and include a plan to deliver services with the 
least cost to Bolsa Chica residents and least impact to the city's residents. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the city wants the project to be a balanced community with a mix 
of land uses; consistent with city development standards, and designed as if it 
would be annexed to the city. The city also wants historically significant 
structures and cultural artifacts preserved. DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
